data.title: Kona Marathon: Three-peat for Gillette; first win for his wife
data.meta_description: More than 1,100 runners complete Kona Marathon, family fun runs; Luis De La Torre pipped for third in half-marathon
data.text:
Photography by David O. Baldwin | Special to Hawaii 24/7

Karin Stanton | Hawaii 24/7 Contributing Editor

and Finn Gallagher | Hawaii 24/7 Student Reporter

The UCC Coffee Kunitake Farms Kona Marathon, Half Marathon and Family Fun Runs proved once again they are family events â€” from husband-and-wife champions to three generations of the Deloziers.

Indiana couple Justin, 27, and Melissa Gillette made is look easy Sunday at Keauhou Beach Resort, snatching the marathon crowns. He finished in a time of 2 hours, 34 minutes and 53 seconds; she did it in 3:07:51, and 3rd finisher overall.

Also keeping it in the family were professional triathletes Belinda and Justin Granger. She finished the marathon 4th overall in 3:10:58; he finished the half-marathon 2nd overall in 1:15:43.

Maik Twelsiek’s time of 1:14:42 was good enough to earn him the half-marathon title, while Kona’s top finisher Luis De La Torre sprinted to the finish with Jason Braswell, was held off for 4th place with a time of 1:16:06.

In the 5K family fun run, three generations of Delozier were on the starting line â€” from grandchildren Tessa and Lily to grandma Marlene.

This family was chasing their potential with the two little preschoolers Tessa and Lily, both 5, completing their third 5k race event this year. While their mom, aunt, and grandma also opted for the 5k, their father Ryan Delozier, was racing the full marathon.

Wife Christy Delozier said they were visiting the Big Island from Washington state for a wedding and on the spur of the moment decided they might as well do the racing event.

Others were on a mission at Sunday’s event.

“Always we need people who care about charity for the greater purpose to help the people with pancreatic cancer,” said Team Hope captain Sue Lonsway.

Team Hope, which included 11 members racing Sunday, had raised $58,000 to support pancreatic cancer research. Pancreatic cancer is the fourth leading cause of cancer death, yet only 2 percent of the government cancer funding benefits this cause.

Team Hope included Lonsway’s two daughters, Cammie and Delaney, and her good friend, all of whom came from Ohio to help fight this deadly cancer that runs in her family.

Behind the scenes, a worker at the Ueshima Coffee Company sponsor’s tent for 9 years, Peggy Stevens as been part of this event for a long time and appreciates how the race brings the community together.

She said she likes to see familiar faces appearing throughout all the races over the years. She feeds positivity to all the racers so that this race would be memorable for them.

Among the more than 1,100 runners was Frank Shorter, a 1972 Olympic gold medalist in the marathon, who was competing for the 15th time. He was 88th overall in the half-marathon, clocking in at 1:05:36.
